  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in the vast majority of jurisdictions worldwide, including China. It involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through complex transactions or financial systems, to make it appear as if it came from legitimate sources. \n\nIn China, money laundering is explicitly prohibited under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**, which was enacted in 2006 and amended in 2007. The law establishes a comprehensive legal framework to prevent and combat money laundering activities, requiring financial institutions and specific non-financial entities to implement strict anti-money laundering (AML) measures, such as customer due diligence, record-keeping, and reporting suspicious transactions.\n\nViolations of anti-money laundering laws in China can result in severe penalties, including hefty fines, confiscation of assets, and criminal charges leading to imprisonment. The Chinese government, in line with its commitment to maintaining financial stability and combating corruption, actively enforces these laws and cooperates with international organizations to combat money laundering globally.",
